issue.body:
fix #1171 

The cases `Assert.That(null, Is.Not.Empty)` and `Is.Not.Null.Or.Empty` will continue to fail as they are written. The 'null' value cannot be checked to see if the EmptyConstraint types can be applied because this is lost.

If the test were rewritten as:

```
string actual = null;
Assert.That(actual, Is.Empty);

//or

Assert.That((string)null, Is.Empty);
```

I think that most tests will have the type information like the rewritten test cases as opposed to having just `null`.

These tests throw the AssertionException as expected. If the type cannot be applied, (not string, collection, or DirectoryInfo), the ArgumentException will be thrown.

body:
Based on my understanding, the last condition `Assert.That("", Is.Not.Null.Or.Empty)` is not an issue. That test roughly translates to:

```
var expected = "";
if (expected != null || expected == "")
{
    // all ok
}
else
{
    throw AssertionException();
}
```

If it were rewritten as `Assert.That("", Is.Not.Null.And.Not.Empty));`, the test passes. I can understand the confusion because it is similar to the string.IsNullOrEmpty(), which is how I also first read this test.

I am working on a PR that will allow a test to be written like this:

```
string actual = null;
Assert.That(actual, Is.Empty);

//or

Assert.That((string)null, Is.Empty);
```

If the tests were written as `Assert.That(null, Is.Empty)`, they would continue to fail.

With out the type information, .NET is not able to determine the type of the value. Ex:
`null` _(does not know you intend it to be a string)_
`(string)null` _(works because .NET sees this as a string that is null)._
